{"id":"astro-ph/0410053","submitter":"Jean-Pierre Lasota","authors":"Jean-Pierre Lasota (IAP) and Noam Soker (Technion)","title":"Why there are no jets from cataclysmic variable stars","comments":"To be published in \"The astrophysics of cataclysmic variables and\n  related objects\", ASP Conf. Ser., eds. J.M. Hameury and J.P. Lasota","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph","license":null,"abstract":"  We argue that the recent thermal model of jet launching by young stellar\nobjects, when applied to system containing disk-accreting white dwarfs\nnaturally explain the otherwise astonishing absence of jets in cataclysmic\nvariable stars. Thermal launching is possible when the accreted material is\nstrongly shocked due to large gradients of physical quantities in the boundary\nlayer (or at the inner boundary of a truncated disk) and then cools on a time\nscale longer than its ejection time from the disk. In our framework the\nmagnetic fields are weak, and serve only to recollimate the outflow at large\ndistances from the source, or to initiate the shock, but not as a jet-driving\nagent. Using criteria for shock formation and mass ejection, we find the mass\naccretion rate above which jets can be launched from boundary layers around\naccreting white dwarfs to be ~10^{-6} Mo/y, which explains the absence of jets\nin cataclysmic variable stars and their presence in other white-dwarf accreting\nsystems such as super-soft X-ray sources, symbiotic stars and classical novae.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sun, 3 Oct 2004 16:57:01 GMT"}],"update_date":"2007-05-23"}
